    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/assessment-methods.ptx" />

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/reflection.ptx"/>

    
    <p>
        The <term>range of a function</term> is the set of all possible output values (typically <m>y</m>-values) that result from substituting all valid input values (the domain) into the function.
    </p>

    <p>
        In simple terms, while the domain tells us what can go <em>into</em> a function, the range tells us what can come <em>out</em> of it.
    </p>

    <p>
        For example, consider the function:
    </p>

    <p>
        <me>
            f(x)=x^2
        </me>
    </p>

    <p>
        Since any real number squared is either positive or zero, the output can never be a negative number. Thus, the range is all non-negative real numbers.
    </p>

    <p>
        <me>
            \text{Range} = [0,\infty)
        </me>
    </p>

    <paragraphs>

        <title>Rules for Finding the Range of a Function</title>

        <p>
            The following guidelines are commonly used when finding the range of functions:
        </p>

        <p>
            <ol marker="(a)">
                <li>
                    <p>
                        The range of an odd-degree polynomial function (like a line or a cubic) is generally all real numbers, <m>(-\infty, \infty)</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                    <p>
                        The range of an even-degree polynomial (like a parabola) has a minimum or maximum value determined by its vertex.
                    </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                    <p>
                        For a basic square root function, the output is always non-negative, meaning the range starts at zero: <m>[0, \infty)</m>. This shifts if the graph is translated vertically.
                    </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                    <p>
                        The range of a basic exponential function is all positive real numbers, <m>(0, \infty)</m>, because the function approaches a horizontal asymptote but never quite reaches it.
                    </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                    <p>
                        For a rational function, find the horizontal asymptote to see which <m>y</m>-value the function never reaches.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>

    </paragraphs>

    <figure xml:id="fig-range-graphs">

        <caption>Graphs illustrating how to determine the range of a function.</caption>

        <image xml:id="tikz-range-graphs" width="90%">

            <shortdescription>
                Two graphs used to determine ranges. The first graph is a parabola shifted up by 1. The second graph is an exponential curve with a horizontal asymptote at y=0.
            </shortdescription>

            <latex-image>
                \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.9]

                    % ================= LEFT GRAPH ===================
                    \begin{scope}[shift={(-5,0)}]

                        % Axes
                        \draw[-&gt;, thick] (-3.5,0) -- (3.5,0) node[below] {$x$};
                        \draw[-&gt;, thick] (0,-1) -- (0,5) node[left] {$y$};

                        % Graph
                        \draw[blue, thick, domain=-2:2, samples=100]
                        plot (\x, {\x*\x + 1});

                        % Labels
                        \node at (0,1) [below right] {\small $(0,1)$};
                        \node at (1.5,4.5) {\small $y=x^2+1$};

                        \node[align=left, text width=4.5cm, font=\small]
                        at (0,-2)
                        {Look at the vertical spread.\\
                        Range: $[1,\infty)$};

                    \end{scope}

                    % ================= RIGHT GRAPH ===================
                    \begin{scope}[shift={(5,0)}]

                        % Axes
                        \draw[-&gt;, thick] (-4,0) -- (4,0) node[below] {$x$};
                        \draw[-&gt;, thick] (0,-1) -- (0,4) node[left] {$y$};

                        % Horizontal Asymptote
                        \draw[dashed, red, thick] (-4,0) -- (4,0);

                        % Graph
                        \draw[red, thick, domain=-4:1.3, samples=100]
                        plot (\x, {exp(\x)});

                        % Labels
                        \node at (1.5,3.2) {\small $y=e^x$};

                        \node[align=left, text width=4.5cm, font=\small]
                        at (0,-2)
                        {The curve never touches $y=0$.\\
                        Range: $(0,\infty)$};

                    \end{scope}

                \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>

        </image>

    </figure>

    <paragraphs>

        <title>How to Find the Range of a Function</title>

        <p>
            To find the range algebraically, you can often set <m>f(x) = y</m>, solve for <m>x</m> in terms of <m>y</m>, and then find the domain of this new inverse relation. The values of <m>y</m> that make this relation defined are the range of the original function.
        </p>

        <p>
            To find the range graphically, scan the <m>y</m>-axis from bottom to top. Identify the lowest point and the highest point of the graph, keeping an eye out for horizontal asymptotes or holes.
        </p>

    </paragraphs>

    <exploration>

        <title>Range of a Function</title>

        <interactive
            xml:id="interactive-range-explorer"
            platform="jsxgraph"
            width="90%"
            aspect="16:9"
            source="jsxgraph/range-function.js">

            <slate
                xml:id="random-range-board"
                surface="jsxboard"
                aspect="16:9"/>

            <instructions>

                <p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Click the <alert>New Random Function</alert> button to generate different types of functions.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Observe the <term>shaded region</term> along the <m>y</m>-axis. The shaded region represents the <term>range</term> of the function.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Notice how parabolas have a strict minimum or maximum <m>y</m>-value (the vertex).
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Observe how rational and exponential functions interact with horizontal asymptotes, causing certain <m>y</m>-values to be excluded.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Use the graph's highest and lowest points to predict the range before checking the displayed answer.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </p>

            </instructions>

        </interactive>

    </exploration>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Find the range of the quadratic function <m>f(x) = x^2 - 4</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                The graph of <m>f(x) = x^2</m> is a parabola opening upwards with its vertex at <m>(0,0)</m>. 
            </p>
            <p>
                The <m>-4</m> shifts the entire graph down by 4 units along the <m>y</m>-axis. Therefore, the lowest possible output value is <m>-4</m>. Since it opens upwards, it extends to positive infinity.
            </p>
            <p>
                The range is <m>[-4, \infty)</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Determine the range of the rational function <m>g(x) = \frac{1}{x}</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                To find the range, let <m>y = \frac{1}{x}</m> and solve for <m>x</m>:
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>x = \frac{1}{y}</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                We can see that this expression is undefined when <m>y = 0</m>. This indicates there is a horizontal asymptote at <m>y = 0</m>. The function can produce any output except zero.
            </p>
            <p>
                The range is <m>(-\infty, 0) \cup (0, \infty)</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Calculate the range of the absolute value function <m>h(x) = -|x| + 3</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                The absolute value expression <m>|x|</m> is always greater than or equal to 0. Multiplying it by <m>-1</m> means <m>-|x|</m> is always less than or equal to 0.
            </p>
            <p>
                Adding 3 shifts the maximum value up to 3. The graph is a "V" shape opening downwards with its peak at <m>y = 3</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                Because the maximum output is 3 and it goes downwards forever, the range is <m>(-\infty, 3]</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Determine the range of the function <m>p(x)</m> represented by the graph below.
            </p>
            <figure xml:id="fig-range-bounded-graph">
                <caption>Graph of a bounded function</caption>
                <image xml:id="tikz-range-bounded-graph" width="70%">
                    <shortdescription>A curve on a coordinate plane with a minimum y-value of -2 and a maximum y-value of 4.</shortdescription>
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.9]
                            % Axes
                            \draw[-&gt;, thick] (-4,0) -- (6,0) node[below] {$x$};
                            \draw[-&gt;, thick] (0,-3) -- (0,5) node[left] {$y$};
                            
                            % Ticks
                            \draw (0, -2) -- (-0.1, -2) node[left] {$-2$};
                            \draw (0, 4) -- (-0.1, 4) node[left] {$4$};
                            
                            % The curve
                            \draw[very thick, blue] (-2,-2) .. controls (1,5) and (3,-1) .. (5,4);
                            
                            % Endpoints
                            \filldraw[blue] (-2,-2) circle (2.5pt); % Solid dot
                            \filldraw[fill=white, draw=blue, thick] (5,4) circle (2.5pt); % Open dot
                            
                            % Dashed reference lines
                            \draw[dashed, gray] (-2,0) -- (-2,-2) -- (0,-2);
                            \draw[dashed, gray] (5,0) -- (5,4) -- (0,4);
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </figure>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                To find the range from a graph, we look at the vertical spread of the curve along the <m>y</m>-axis from bottom to top.
            </p>
            <p>
                The lowest point on the graph is at a <m>y</m>-value of <m>-2</m>. Because the dot is solid, <m>-2</m> is included in the range. The highest point on the graph reaches a <m>y</m>-value of <m>4</m>. Though there is an open dot at the endpoint, a previous peak also reaches up to 4 (or near it). However, looking closely at the endpoint, the open dot at <m>y = 4</m> means it strictly bounds the graph without including 4. Assuming the curve's local maximum does not exceed 4, the highest value approached is 4.
            </p>
            <p>
                The range consists of all <m>y</m>-values from <m>-2</m> up to, but not including, <m>4</m>. In interval notation, this is <m>[-2, 4)</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Find the range of the rational function <m>q(x)</m> plotted in the graph below.
            </p>
            <figure xml:id="fig-range-asymptote-graph">
                <caption>Graph of a function with a horizontal asymptote</caption>
                <image xml:id="tikz-range-asymptote-graph" width="70%">
                    <shortdescription>A rational function graphed in two pieces, showing a horizontal asymptote at y = 1.</shortdescription>
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.9]
                            % Axes
                            \draw[-&gt;, thick] (-5,0) -- (5,0) node[below] {$x$};
                            \draw[-&gt;, thick] (0,-4) -- (0,5) node[left] {$y$};
                            
                            % Horizontal Asymptote
                            \draw[dashed, very thick, red] (-5,1) -- (5,1) node[above left] {$y=1$};
                            \draw (0.1, 1) -- (-0.1, 1) node[below left, text=black] {$1$};
                            
                            % Vertical Asymptote
                            \draw[dashed, gray] (-2,-4) -- (-2,5);

                            % The curves
                            \draw[very thick, purple, domain=-5:-2.2, samples=50] plot (\x, {1/(\x+2) + 1});
                            \draw[very thick, purple, domain=-1.8:5, samples=50] plot (\x, {1/(\x+2) + 1});
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </figure>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Observing the vertical spread of the graph, the arrows point downward to <m>-\infty</m> and upward to <m>\infty</m>, meaning the function covers extreme positive and negative values.
            </p>
            <p>
                However, there is a red dashed line representing a horizontal asymptote at <m>y = 1</m>. The function levels off as it approaches this line horizontally, but never produces an output of exactly 1.
            </p>
            <p>
                Since the graph covers all <m>y</m>-values except <m>1</m>, the range is all real numbers except 1. In interval notation, this is <m>(-\infty, 1) \cup (1, \infty)</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <exercises xml:id="exercise-range-function">

        <exercise>

            <statement>

                <p>
                    Find the range of each of the following functions.
                </p>

                <p>
                    <ol marker="1." cols="2">

                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>f(x)=3x-5</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>

                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>g(x)=x^2+2</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>

                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>h(x)=\sqrt{x}</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>

                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>p(x)=|x-4|</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>

                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>q(x)=2^x</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>

                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>r(x)=\dfrac{1}{x} + 3</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>

                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>s(x)=-x^2</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>

                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>t(x)=\sqrt{x+5}-1</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>

                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>u(x)=e^x - 2</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>

                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>v(x)=7</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>

                    </ol>
                </p>

            </statement>

            <answer>

                <p>

                    <ol marker="1." cols="2">

                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>(-\infty,\infty)</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>

                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>[2,\infty)</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>

                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>[0,\infty)</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>

                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>[0,\infty)</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>

                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>(0,\infty)</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>

                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>(-\infty,3)\cup(3,\infty)</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>

                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>(-\infty,0]</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>

                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>[-1,\infty)</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>

                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>(-2,\infty)</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>

                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>[7,7]</m> or simply <m>\{7\}</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>

                    </ol>

                </p>

            </answer>

        </exercise>
        
    </exercises>

</section>
